part of that conversation
tomorrow.

27:45.597 --> 27:56.174 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

27:56.174 --> 28:02.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
candidates crisscross Iowa to
win last-minute votes; changing
perception

28:02.814 --> 28:07.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through stories of autism; and a
photojournalist remembered
through the stunning photos she

28:07.386 --> 28:10.222 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
left behind.

28:10.222 --> 28:16.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, many high school
seniors have finished college
applications. And now they're

28:16.395 --> 28:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
waiting to find out whether
taking advanced courses,
prepping for entrance exams and
agonizing

28:21.600 --> 28:25.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over essays will all pay off.

28:25.070 --> 28:31.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A new report from the Harvard
Graduate School of Education
calls on colleges to lower the

28:31.009 --> 28:37.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pressure on students to impress
admissions committees by racking
up achievements and

28:37.249 --> 28:42.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accolades. The report, called
"Turning the Tide," recommends
limiting the number of advanced

28:42.588 --> 28:47.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
placement classes and
extracurricular activities that
students can list on
applications.

28:47.826 --> 28:53.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Instead, it emphasizes community
service and other changes.

28:53.465 --> 28:57.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Richard Weissbourd is the lead
author of the report and he's a
senior lecturer at the Harvard

28:57.269 --> 29:00.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Graduate School of Education.

29:00.706 --> 29:03.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Richard Weissbourd, thank you
very much for joining us.

29:03.875 --> 29:07.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is it that's wrong with the
college application process
right now?

29:07.379 --> 29:09.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD, Harvard
Graduate School of Education:
Well, I think, right now, what

29:09.881 --> 29:15.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students are doing is they're --
some students are racking up
accomplishments. I think they

29:15.587 --> 29:20.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think, particularly in affluent
communities, that the goal is
long brag sheets.

29:20.726 --> 29:24.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the message we're trying to
send here is that the goal isn't
long brag sheets. The

29:24.696 --> 29:30.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
goal is meaningful academic
engagement and spirited,
passionate learning, and it's
meaningful

29:30.335 --> 29:34.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ethical engagement. It's being
involved in your community,
concern for others, concern

29:34.339 --> 29:37.209 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for the greater good,
for the public good.

29:37.209 --> 29:39.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So what is it
that students are emphasizing
that you would like to see

29:39.745 --> 29:42.481 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
less of?

29:42.481 --> 29:48.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD: Well, I
think one of the things that
they are very focused on is
creating

29:48.654 --> 29:54.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- accumulating extracurricular
activities, accumulating A.P.
courses.

29:54.626 --> 29:58.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what the admission deans who
have endorsed this report -- and
over 50 admission deans

29:58.997 --> 30:03.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have endorsed it -- what they're
saying, what they're saying
collectively, and it's very

30:03.168 --> 30:08.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
important that they're saying it
collectively, you know, they're
on the same page about this,

30:08.306 --> 30:11.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they're on the same highway --
what they're saying is, you
know, you're not going to be

30:11.743 --> 30:15.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
penalized if you take a lot of
A.P. courses, but you don't need
to. You're not going to

30:15.013 --> 30:19.384 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
be penalized if you take
a few A.P. courses.

30:19.384 --> 30:25.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's fine. It's totally
appropriate to list a couple,
two or three extracurricular
activities

30:25.457 --> 30:28.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that have been meaningful to you
and to describe why they're
meaningful to you. We're not
looking

30:28.326 --> 30:31.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for long lists of
activities either.

30:31.830 --> 30:37.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, as you said,
it is about 50 colleges and
universities that signed on.

30:37.135 --> 30:41.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were clearly some that
didn't sign on. Aren't there
going to be schools out there

30:41.373 --> 30:46.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that do care about some of the
ways these students perform in
ways that you're saying

30:46.912 --> 30:48.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
should be de-emphasized?

30:48.814 --> 30:53.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Isn't there going to be a
different set of criteria now at
different schools?

30:53.285 --> 30:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD: Well, you
know, I think there's a few
different issues here.

30:56.621 --> 31:01.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All the Ivy League schools have
signed on. A lot of the very
selective schools have signed

31:01.259 --> 31:07.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on. And many non -- schools that
are not especially selective
have signed on. And I think, you

31:07.999 --> 31:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
know, the criteria are still
that they're looking for
students who are academically

31:12.304 --> 31:16.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rigorous, but they're also
saying we're looking for
students who lead well-balanced
lives,

31:16.441 --> 31:19.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who are involved in
their communities.

31:19.144 --> 31:24.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're not involved in
community service as an
accomplishment, as a way to
impress

31:24.416 --> 31:28.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
admissions officers. They are
involved in things that are
meaningful to them and
potentially

31:28.987 --> 31:33.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
transformative to them and
enable them to have experiences
of diversity across race,

31:33.825 --> 31:37.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
class, culture, also political
and religious orientation.

31:37.696 --> 31:43.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is there a risk
there, though, Richard
Weissbourd, that you create a
different

31:43.068 --> 31:47.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of pressure on students, to
rack up the kind of community
service that you're saying

31:47.606 --> 31:50.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you and others want to
see them engage in?

31:50.976 --> 31:55.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD: Well, you
know, I think that there are
some students and parents who

31:55.313 --> 31:59.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are going to game the
system. That's always true.

31:59.050 --> 32:03.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But part of what we're saying is
-- or part of what we're
motiving them to do is to do

32:03.421 --> 32:08.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forms of community engagement
that we think will be
transformative for them.

32:08.527 --> 32:13.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And one of the things about
community service and community
engagement is, if students have

32:13.064 --> 32:18.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
authentic choices, and it's
well-structured,
well-supervised, they have time
for reflection

32:18.470 --> 32:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with adults and with peers, even
if it's mandatory, it tends to
be helpful and it often is
transformative.

32:24.810 --> 32:29.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's a powerful learning
experience. So you might even do
it for the wrong reason, but

32:29.281 --> 32:32.017 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
end up getting a lot
of benefit from it.

32:32.017 --> 32:35.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So you think
that's the way it works, you
mandate somebody to do community

32:35.053 --> 32:39.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
service and then you believe
they will get something out of
it?

32:39.491 --> 32:45.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD: Well, we're
not mandating it. We are
encouraging it. We are saying
that,

32:45.463 --> 32:51.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, it's not about doing a
brief stint overseas. It is
about doing something
meaningful,

32:51.937 --> 32:55.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing something in a diverse
group, doing it for a year, nine
months to a year, doing

32:55.540 --> 32:59.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it for a sustained
period of time.

32:59.077 --> 33:02.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the chances are greater that
you're going to get something
out of that kind of experience,

33:02.914 --> 33:05.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and you're going to be able to
describe in the application in a
way that's meaningful

33:05.717 --> 33:08.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and expresses what was
meaningful about it to you.

33:08.820 --> 33:12.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's a
report certainly worth looking
at.

33:12.257 --> 33:15.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Richard Weissbourd at the
Harvard School of Education, we
thank you.

33:15.060 --> 33:25.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICHARD WEISSBOURD: Well, thank
you. It's a pleasure to be here.

