adults.

44:08.880 --> 44:11.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN DONVAN: Well, yes.

44:11.048 --> 44:15.152 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And our thought is that the
people who fought battles over
the last 75 years to get their

44:15.152 --> 44:18.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kids out of institutions and
into schools where legally they
were barred -- schools

44:18.623 --> 44:19.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
could say, we're not going
to educate your kid.

44:19.690 --> 44:22.093 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. Yes.

44:22.093 --> 44:26.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Things moved so
much, not perfectly, but they
moved so much that we want that
message

44:26.163 --> 44:30.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be an inspiration for the job
that's still there to done.

44:30.167 --> 44:33.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You talk about
things being shrouded in shame,
secrecy, and ignorance.

44:33.104 --> 44:36.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Give me an example. What
do you mean by that?

44:36.841 --> 44:39.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: Well, parents were
told to put their children in
institutions. And that was

44:39.844 --> 44:42.613 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the thing that you did.

44:42.613 --> 44:47.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Keeping them at home, nobody did
that. And if they did, they hid
them. And if they put

44:47.685 --> 44:52.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them in institutions, they
didn't tell anyone. It was what
doctors told you to do.

44:52.757 --> 44:56.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: And to forget about
your kids. They would say, put
your kids there, go home,

44:56.327 --> 45:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take care of your kids who are
normal, and try to forget those
kids. And some parents,

45:01.098 --> 45:04.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
many parents did that through
about the 1950s or '60s.

45:04.235 --> 45:08.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The whole history
you tell from back then, even
through to today, is

45:08.005 --> 45:12.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
filled with confusions,
arguments, counterarguments.

45:12.076 --> 45:19.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, everything seems to be on
the table, definitions,
responses, even to today,
whether there's

45:19.183 --> 45:22.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
an actual epidemic,
all of this. Right?

45:22.620 --> 45:27.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Well, that's
because autism itself is
actually not a very clearly
defined concept.

45:27.858 --> 45:32.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the proof of that is, the
definition has changed again and
again and again over the

45:32.997 --> 45:39.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years. It's a condition where
there's no DNA test, there's no
cheek swab, biological marker.

45:39.704 --> 45:44.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Autism is defined by looking at
behaviors. And everybody looks
at behaviors differently.

45:44.442 --> 45:49.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, over the years, autism has
almost been a diagnosis in the
eye of the beholder, which

45:49.280 --> 45:53.618 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
allows for all kinds of
arguments and dissension and
theories and competing therapies
to come

45:53.618 --> 45:55.853 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
into play.

45:55.853 --> 46:00.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: But there's one
thing that's been a constant,
which is the parental love.

46:00.191 --> 46:04.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you read the stories in this
book, throughout all of the
battles, all of the fights, all

46:04.562 --> 46:08.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the controversies, it's all
about fighting for their kids.

46:08.165 --> 46:11.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's a story,
that runs through the book,
parents, and then activists, of

46:11.435 --> 46:12.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
course, but parents
really leading the way.

46:12.937 --> 46:12.903 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Parents were...

46:12.903 --> 46:14.338 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

46:14.338 --> 46:17.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: Right, which is
why this is -- this isn't just
-- this isn't a book for

46:17.408 --> 46:22.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the autism community, per se.
It's for everybody who's ever
had a child, who's ever cared
about

46:22.279 --> 46:25.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
somebody. What wouldn't
you do for your child?

46:25.216 --> 46:28.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Was there a
character that jumps out at you
that you could tell us about?

46:28.419 --> 46:32.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Our friend Donald
Triplett was the first child
diagnosed with autism. Caren

46:32.056 --> 46:37.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
found him back in 2007.

46:37.228 --> 46:40.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You found a phone number that
you thought might be his, and
you called him up. And we

46:40.398 --> 46:43.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weren't sure it was the guy who
showed up in the medical
literature as case one, because

46:43.501 --> 46:45.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the only name was
given was Donald T.

46:45.670 --> 46:48.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And what did you hear?

46:48.372 --> 46:54.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CAREN ZUCKER: I got his
answering machine. And he
answered, "Hello, this is Donald
Triplett.

46:54.478 --> 46:59.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Happy June. Happy fall. Happy
Christmas. And a great 2007 to
you."

46:59.050 --> 47:02.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I knew as soon as -- it was,
like, John, it's -- we found
him. We got him. This is

47:02.586 --> 47:05.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Donald. We definitely
have Donald.

47:05.056 --> 47:08.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN DONVAN: He's such a
wonderful guy, Donald, but the
wonderful thing about his story,
a

47:08.859 --> 47:12.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
couple of things, one is that
who is and who he has turned out
to be. He was very, very

47:12.730 --> 47:15.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
severely disabled as a child.

47:15.433 --> 47:19.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the role model for the
diagnosis of autism. He couldn't
use language effectively, didn't

47:19.036 --> 47:25.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
connect with people. And, today,
he has a wonderful life as a man
in his 80s. He's living

47:25.276 --> 47:28.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
alone in a little town in
Mississippi. He plays golf all
the time. He travels the world.

47:28.846 --> 47:31.082 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He has friends.

47:31.082 --> 47:34.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the other thing about that
story is his community and the
role they played in it.

47:34.885 --> 47:37.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: They have totally
embraced him. They accepted him
for being different, so

47:37.555 --> 47:39.390 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he wasn't different.

47:39.390 --> 47:42.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Given this sort
of history of confusion,
counterarguments, what do you

47:42.560 --> 47:44.495 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
see happening now?

47:44.495 --> 47:50.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: We're at a point
now where things aren't perfect,
but we have at least tried

47:50.067 --> 47:53.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to address the challenges of
children with autism in ways
that we weren't doing nearly

47:53.104 --> 47:56.407 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sufficiently even 25 years ago.

47:56.407 --> 48:02.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're in public schools.
They're getting direct education
and direct therapy. But that's,

48:02.680 --> 48:06.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we think, the job only being
half-done, because there's a
whole -- something's going to
happen

48:06.584 --> 48:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to all of these kids, and
they're basically going to grow
up -- like, your son has just

48:09.120 --> 48:11.222 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
turned 21.

48:11.222 --> 48:14.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: And his whole
life, he's had incredible
support and services, because of

48:14.825 --> 48:16.293 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
the parents that
fought for them.

48:16.293 --> 48:17.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: You
see more acceptance.

48:17.061 --> 48:18.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN DONVAN: Definitely.

48:18.562 --> 48:20.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You see more
understanding in the society.

48:20.898 --> 48:22.767 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: For children.

48:22.767 --> 48:26.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For children. But
you still see many problems.

48:26.403 --> 48:29.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Well, there's a lot
of dissension and controversy of
all kinds. There always

48:29.106 --> 48:31.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
been in the autism community.

48:31.475 --> 48:35.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have lived through some of
them. The whole vaccine debate
has been one of them. There

48:35.579 --> 48:40.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are disagreements over whether
autism is something that should
be always and all the time
embraced

48:40.284 --> 48:44.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and celebrated as just a
different way to be human, or
whether autism sometimes can

48:44.789 --> 48:50.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be really so debilitating to
individuals that you want to do
something to change those
disabilities

48:50.494 --> 48:53.164 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in them.

48:53.164 --> 48:56.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are fault lines all of the
time. But I don't think there's
a fault line on this

48:56.534 --> 49:00.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
question of, what do we do about
adults? I think everybody agrees
it's a problem, but

49:00.504 --> 49:06.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nobody really has a solution.
And I don't sense that people
are loving the adults the

49:06.610 --> 49:11.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way they have learned to love
kids, because the truth is,
they're not going to be cute

49:11.182 --> 49:14.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the same as kids are. And
they shouldn't have to be cute
to deserve and merit our
attention

49:14.218 --> 49:16.353 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and support.

49:16.353 --> 49:18.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you have a
last word on that? Is it a
cultural issue? A political

49:18.322 --> 49:20.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
issue? Or what do see?

49:20.658 --> 49:28.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: I think it's
cultural first, that some adults
are -- they're not embraced,

49:28.432 --> 49:31.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that people -- they're unknown
still. People aren't used to
having adults with autism
around.

49:31.902 --> 49:35.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: A little story we
tell in our book is the perfect
thing.

49:35.239 --> 49:38.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It happened a few years ago on a
bus in New Jersey. There was a
kid sitting on a bus.

49:38.576 --> 49:44.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was about 19 years old -- 17
years old. He's learning how to
ride the bus. His teacher

49:44.248 --> 49:47.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is in the back of the bus. He's
been for weeks showing him how
to ride the bus, and he's

49:47.551 --> 49:51.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
been fading himself
farther and farther back.

49:51.155 --> 49:55.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the kid starts making some
noises and flipping his fingers
and rocking in an odd

49:55.025 --> 49:59.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way. And two passengers behind
him start getting agitated about
this. And they start saying

49:59.396 --> 50:03.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to this kid, "Hey, weirdo,
what's you're problem?"

50:03.868 --> 50:07.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the great -- yes, the great
thing is what happened next.

50:07.438 --> 50:10.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAREN ZUCKER: Is that he had
been riding a bus for a few
weeks. So the people on the

50:10.674 --> 50:17.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bus were used to him. And some
guy stood up and said, "Hey,
he's got autism. What's your

50:17.882 --> 50:20.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
problem? What's your reason
for acting like a jerk?"

50:20.951 --> 50:24.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And what happened is a
community formed around him.

50:24.321 --> 50:26.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN DONVAN: Both the problem
was there and the solution was
there.

50:26.790 --> 50:28.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right. That's
one of the many stories told in
the book.

50:28.826 --> 50:31.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the book is "In a Different
Key: The Story of Autism."

50:31.462 --> 50:37.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Caren Zucker, John
Donvan, thank you both.

50:37.067 --> 50:41.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN DONVAN: Thanks,
Jeff, very much.

50:41.805 --> 50:48.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
CAREN ZUCKER: Thank
you for having us.

50:48.345 --> 50:53.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight, a
young life dedicated to
capturing beauty cut short by

50:53.150 --> 50:55.452 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
violence.

50:55.452 --> 51:00.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Al-Qaida militants attacked a
hotel in Burkina Faso on Friday.
Thirty people were killed,

51:00.691 --> 51:05.195 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
including two who worked
for Amnesty International.

51:05.195 --> 51:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the amnesty workers was a
French-Moroccan photographer
named Leila Alaoui.

51:10.000 --> 51:15.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Earlier today, we spoke with one
of Alaoui's closest friends,
Aida Alami, who is also a

51:15.406 --> 51:20.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
journalist. We reached her by
phone at Alaoui's funeral in
Marrakesh, Morocco.

51:20.377 --> 51:26.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AIDA ALAMI, Friend of Leila
Alaoui: She was a luminous,
really vibrant person. She was

51:26.116 --> 51:30.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really positive. She loved her
job. She loved her friends.

51:30.521 --> 51:37.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And she was a very active young
woman, traveling all the time,
working on topics she really

51:37.227 --> 51:41.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
loved. She was very focused,
very dedicated to her work and
her subject.

51:41.565 --> 51:47.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, there's an anecdote I have
heard her say a lot, is that she
was French-Moroccan,

51:47.871 --> 51:53.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so, because of her French
passport, she could travel
everywhere, and she was always
really

51:53.777 --> 52:00.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interested in all these people
who could not cross borders and
so on. And she was wondering

52:00.017 --> 52:04.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
why they were trying -- they
were risking their lives to go
to the other side.

52:04.621 --> 52:12.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She had a way of photographing
people like not many people, I
think, can do it. And so

52:12.896 --> 52:17.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she started getting to the
portraits -- into doing
portraits all over the world.
She did

52:17.434 --> 52:20.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a lot of human rights
campaigns for free.

52:20.437 --> 52:26.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was just interested in
capturing people and capturing
people who were going through

52:26.276 --> 52:31.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hard times. And the reason she
was in Burkina is I know that
she was taking photos of
powerful

52:31.515 --> 52:35.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
women. And she was actually
sending me once she was there a
lot of pictures of these women

52:35.386 --> 52:39.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that she was photographing, and
reported on subjects where she
was embedded for a long

52:39.990 --> 52:45.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
time, for example, the plight of
Sub-Saharan Africans in Morocco.

52:45.329 --> 52:51.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was so into it that I
couldn't see Leila without her
getting tons of phone calls of

52:51.669 --> 52:55.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
undocumented people telling her
they were trying to cross, and
her giving them advice

52:55.572 --> 52:59.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and tell them, "No, don't
risk your life, don't cross."

52:59.510 --> 53:05.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was constantly trying to
help them find a doctor, find
money for them. One day, I

53:05.783 --> 53:10.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was reporting on sub-Saharan
migrants in Morocco, and she
said told me, "Oh, well, this
afternoon

53:10.521 --> 53:14.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- today, I'm going to be
recording a lot of them all day,
so if you want -- need some

53:14.425 --> 53:17.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
subjects, just come
over to my place."

53:17.227 --> 53:21.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I walked in, and there were,
like, 40 people in her living
room, and she was making

53:21.298 --> 53:37.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dinner for -- I mean, lunch for
them. I mean, she was just very
intense about all her subjects.

53:37.714 --> 53:43.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: That was
remarkable work she did.

53:43.620 --> 53:45.856 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It really was.

